name: Embedding
description: Embedding is the process of putting social media content on a web page. When you see a YouTube video on a blog you’re reading, or a tweet posted on a business’ website you’re checking out, that’s an example of embedding. Embedding is done through HTML code, and most social media sites have an “Embed” option that gives you the exact code you’ll need.
example1: She is embedding a secret message in the image.
example2: The website's design includes the embedding of social media icons for easy sharing.

name: Influencer
description: Influencers are individuals with a presence on social media who use their platform to affect group opinions and behavior. Celebrities who use Twitter, YouTubers with legions of subscribers, and activists organizing on Facebook are all examples of social media influencers.
example1: The social media influencer promoted the product to her followers.
example2: The influencer's recommendation greatly impacted the brand's sales.

name: Content Curation
description: Even if you’re new to tech, chances are you’re not new to social media. Content curation is the process social media sites use to gather and present content (articles, links, videos, images, etc.) that are relevant to a specific topic or a user’s area of interest. Content can be selected manually by a person designated as a curator, or it can be gathered through automated programs that track things like upvoting, likes, hashtags, or analysis of a user’s previous online activity.
example1: Content curation is an essential part of our marketing strategy, ensuring we share valuable and relevant information with our audience.
example2: She spent hours on content curation, selecting the best articles and videos to share on her blog.

name: Business intelligence
description: Business intelligence or BI refers to the technology, software, and strategies that businesses use to collect, analyze, and present data. Data-driven decision-making is a core concept of business intelligence.
